I purchased it from McMillan about 6 years ago and if I have 30 rounds through it, I would be surprised.  I have shot it out to 1000 and it shot sub MOA with factory crap ammo.  So, down to the specs.  It is a Fisher action they use for their benchrest guns; which is a single shot.  It has the Jewell trigger and set to where I like it (about 2lbs, maybe a little less).  It has the McMillan BR muzzle brake which is awesome for recoil without blowing all the sand and dirt all over you.  It has the 20 MOA base on it as well.  Being that I had no intention of shooting it off the bench, I had them install the "Tac-50" stock on it so it breaks down and fits in a Pelican a little easier and also allows the use of their steel bipod.  Also, if you want to mess with your buddies, tell them they can shoot a 50BMG pistol.  HA!!  Kidding.  Don't do that... if you do, video it.

This is the loading and unloading of it (sorry about the broken finger and one handed camera work): http://youtu.be/tpR3aRZ6gwA

So, essentially the rifle is:
http://mcmillanusa.com/mcmillan-rifles-competition-50lbr.php

The Stock and bipod are shown here on the Tac-50:
http://mcmillanusa.com/mcmillan-rifles-tactical-tac-50.php

Scope:
http://www.opticsplanet.net/custom-leupold-mark-4-6-5-20x50mm-lr-t-m1-illuminated-reticle-rifle-scope.html

I was going to sell it without the scope for $4k.  That is the no-haggle, no BS price.  The bench gun goes for $7500 new, the Tac-50 for $8k, so $4k is a steal.  I do have a Leupold Mark 4 6.5-20x50 LRT M1 illuminated TMR for it in Mark 4 rings that I would let go with it for half of retail (retail is $1479.99) and throw in the rings for free and the lens covers (shown in the pics) as well as the ballistic tape on there (with no markings on it).  

As you can see, I have the ballistic data on the side out to 1300 yards.  That can easily be removed and put onto the ballistic tape (on the scope) or a custom dial made by Leupold's custom shop.  Easily enough.

So $4k for the rifle alone, or $4740 with the scope, rings, etc.

title: For Sale:  1885 Enfield marked Short Lever Martini Henry
postcontent:
For sale is a very nice British 1885 Enfield marked Short Lever Martini Henry chambered for the black powder cartridge in .577/450.  It does have a replacement stock that came from the same weapons cache and this stock is dated to around 1900.  The firearm itself made the trip from England to Africa and may have seen action in the Zulu and Boer Wars.  These rifles were then transported to India and kept at the Ft William Arsenal until Britain gifted them to Nepal.   They were used by Nepal until being stockpiled and stored for nearly 80 years.  

 This rifle is has all British proof marks as well as Nepalese marks.  The bore is super shiny and smooth.  This is the nicest example of a Nepal Cache rifle as I have ever seen.  It shoots well too!  I have taken two deer with this rifle and hate to part with it but I have to fund another firearm venture.   I meticulously cleaned and preserved this rifle and it really is a beauty.  

I am included around 20 rounds of ammunition, bayonet, a British leather bandolier and a Victorian pith helmet for a proper display of this piece of history.   
Cash transaction, trades considered.   Thanks!  

Links to more information: 

http://www.martinihenry.com/

http://www.ima-usa.com/militaria/antique-guns/cleaned-complete-guns/british-p-1871-martini-henry-mkii-short-lever-rifle-1870-s-dates-socket-bayonet-cleaned-complete.html

title: For Sale:  Charter Arms Undercover 1st Generation 38 spl 2" barrel
postcontent:
A perfect CCW or backup weapon at just 16oz, 6" long and 4" high. It has a "Hammer Block" safety system which prevents discharge unless the trigger is in the full aft position.

Charter Arms was founded in 1964 by a gun designer who previously worked for Colt, High Standard and Sturm Ruger. Their first offering was the Undercover model.

To make the revolver stronger and able to shoot hot loads the "side plate" design of other manufacturers was replaced with a one-piece frame with fewer moving parts. 

This resulted in the smallest, lightest steel frame revolver with the fewest moving parts built anywhere to that date. The Undercover's high quality, light weight, and reasonable price made it popular with gun enthusiasts and law officers.

The original company went out of business in the 1990s. Since then these revolvers have been built by various companies with variable quality.

This gun is SN 4400xx which identifies it as a 1977 model and built to exacting standards by the original company.

This Undercover is unmarred except for a small nick on the front of one cylinder flute and a small nick on the right side of the barrel at the bore. The bore is mirror bright.

I bought the Undercover in the mid 80s and loaned it to my Daughter who kept it in her night stand. It has only been to the range twice since I bought it, less than 50 rounds.

More pictures can be seen here; http://photobucket.com/charterundercover

I am asking $265.00 OBO.

For those who don't know, the Colt's are no-longer made (1990's for the last 4th generation)and are quite collectible amongst the Colt revolver crowd. postcontent:
The following posted ad is a SCAM!!  It was illegally copied from another Armslist posted ad and violates US copyright laws.

The mounting system is advertised as the newer cross-bolt system, but in fact uses the old two bolt mounting system which has been discontinued because the bolts strip out of the mount and the entire assembly shoots loose, making it worthless.

=============================================

I have a new scope, picatinny rail, rings and accessories to include bayonet for an M92/30 Mosin Nagant and similar models. This scope kit was designed to mount to the existing rear sight easily with no gunsmithing at all. You can return your MN back to original at any time. Includes everything in pictures including allen keys and instructions for mounting picatinny rail. Accessories include Russian Mosin-Nagant Model 1891 socket bayonet - Second Pattern - designed for the Mosin-Nagant Infantry Rifle. These are considered Communist Russian (post-1918), Oiler, 2 slings, 2 double ammo pouches an tool kit.


Includes: 2-7x32MM Variable Power Wide Angle Scout Scope with Duplex Reticle, No Gunsmith Cross Bolt Picatinny Rail Scope Mount, and Low Profile Scope Rings.

Scope Specifications:
+ Manufactured by Aim Sports Inc
+ Magnification: Wide Angle 2~7 Variable Power
+ Duplex Reticle
+ Objective Lens: 32mm
+ One Inch Tube
+ Weight: 9.0 Ounces
+ Length: 10 3/8 inches
+ Extended Eye Relief
+ Matte Black Finish
+ Windage/Elevation: 1 Click = 1/4" @100 Yards
+ Multi-Coated Lenses
+ Bright Optics
+ Sharp Focusing
+ Eye Piece Focus Lock Ring
+ Nitrogen Filled - Fog and Water Proof
+ Shock Proof  Heavy Duty Recoil Design
+ Protective Lens Caps Included

Mount Specifications:
+ New Third Generation Scout Scope Mount.
+ Fits Mosin Nagant 7.62x54R Rifles and Carbines.
+ For Russian, Hungarian and Polish Carbine Models 38 and 44, Finnish Models M27, M28 and Chinese Model 53 with the 2 3/8" Long 1000 Meter Graduated Rear Sight
+ For Rifle Models 91, 91/30, 91/38 and 91/59 with the 3 3/8" Long 2000 Meter Graduated Rear Site
+ Will Fit Finland 7.62x53R M91/30 but not other models. Some Finnish M91/30 rifles have a high handguard and may require higher rings
+ Easy Installation - "No Gunsmithing" Mount Replaces Rear Sight and Bolts into the Rear Sight Base (Note: Some minor fitting may be required)
+ Use with Weaver Style Rings
+ For Extended Eye Relief (EER) Scopes, Hologram and Red Dot Sights
+ Hardened Aluminum Mount with Multiple Picatinny Rail Slots
+ Mounting Hardware and Installation Instructions Included
+ Restore Rifle to Original Configuration by Removing Mount and Reinstalling the Rear Sight

** This new scope mount has been designed to provide lower "visual alignment" mounting for scout scopes. Alloy steel cross bolt mounting to the rear sight base with a locking nut provides a secure installation and insures that this mount will not shoot loose.

The easily installed, "no gunsmithing" mount replaces the rear sight leaf. (Detailed installation instructions are included with the mount). Simply remove the rear sight leaf and leaf spring, then insert and bolt in the scout mount. Attach the included Weaver style rings to the Picatinny mount and install the extended eye relief (EER) scout scope. You can restore the rifle to its original configuration by unbolting the scope and mount and reinstalling the rear sight.

Some Mosin Nagant scope mounts were designed with two short bolts that attach through the side ears of the rear sight base and thread into the scope mount. With extended shooting these bolts strip out the threads in the aluminum scope mount and the mount comes loose. Our mount has been threaded completely through and is fitted with a full length threaded alloy steel cross bolt and retaining nut that securely attaches the scope mount to the rear sight base.

Ring Specifications:
+ Strong Lightweight Aluminum
+ Non-Slip Mounting
+ Matte Black Finish
+ Low Profile
+ One Inch Diameter
+ Fits Weaver Style Bases or Picatinny Rail
